Finally, we revisit the most important language distinction: 
\f2\i peace as a process
\f1\i0  vs 
\f2\i peace as a product
\f1\i0  (or result). Usually when somebody says 
\f2\i peace
\f1\i0 , what they are referring to a static but temporary state of being (death being an exception). Peace as a product are usually what people often mean things like 
\f2\i tranquil
\f1\i0 , 
\f2\i calm
\f1\i0 , or 
\f2\i still
\f1\i0  when they say 
\f2\i peaceful
\f1\i0 . These are states of being that are pleasant and we work to attain them. This work we do to attain pleasant things is a dynamic and continuous process, and how we approach the work we do must change all the time to adapt to changing circumstance. For example, the calm will only last until the storm comes. A bystander who was once enjoying the calm will now do work to return to calm if they are torn away from it; say, they will seek shelter or they will find better weather.\
\
This constant effort to return to good states of being is peace as a process, and is what we will call 
\f2\i the universal piece
\f1\i0 . We call this the universal piece, because peace as a process is something that every Human being can relate to. It is instinctual. We are driven to the products of our peace process. Again with the exception of death, if we reach the product of the peace product then 
\f2\i stop
\f1\i0  the universal piece, then we quickly fall away from this temporary state. Put simply, whatever that product may be, the product of a peace process is unstable and requires active effort to maintain.\
